calligraphy as expression of buddhism ho center for buddhist studies at stanford skip to main content area home home about the center events people academics research resources partners related links search this site ho center for buddhist studies at stanford calligraphy as expression of buddhism date sat jan 8 2011 1 00pm 4 00pm location annenberg auditorium cummings art building program series program series tt & wf chao lectures on buddhist art 2010 11 co sponsor stanford continuing studies speaker s name affiliation kazuaki tanahashi prominent japanese calligrapher kazuaki tanahashi discusses the history aesthetics techniques and practices of east asian calligraphy through the exploration of a single ideograph in a variety of forms the character  read wu in chinese mu in japanese meaning no not beyond frequently appears in the heart sutra the most widely recited text in mahayana buddhism using the new tanahashi halifax translation of the sutra mr tanahashi will explain the meanings of this word in different contexts and then discuss how this character came to represent a central teaching in zen and how it has been rendered in brushwork the lecture will be accompanied by demonstrations of calligraphy agenda lecture with calligraphy demonstration speaker's bio speaker s bio kazuaki tanahashi born and trained in japan has been active in the united states since 1977 a painter and calligrapher he has had solo exhibitions of his brushwork and has taught calligraphy worldwide he is the author of brush mind 1990 and other works on calligraphy as well as moon in a dewdrop 1985 and other translations of the writings of the japanese zen masters dogen and hakuin for more on his work visit his website www brushmind net stanford university international comparative & area studies department of religious studies ho center for buddhist studies at stanford stanford university all rights reserved stanford ca 94305 site development by wired moon
